{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:50:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"421"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/421"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.47,0.15,0.11,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91967"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75436"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"391"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"9750"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31407"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44029"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91967"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a 12-hour history of penile pain and difficulty passing urine. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. The prepuce is retracted and trapped behind the glans, which appears swollen and dusky (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Infiltration with adrenaline","Manual reduction","Urethral catheterisation","Topical betamethasone","Circumcision"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with paraphimosis, a urological emergency in which the prepuce (foreskin) becomes trapped behind the corona of the penis, causing progressive swelling of the prepuce and glans due to venous and lymphatic congestion. If left untreated, arterial compromise can occur leading to tissue ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EManual reduction\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment and should be attempted promptly after applying topical anaesthetic. The technique involves gentle compression of the oedematous tissue to reduce the swelling, followed by replacing the foreskin over the glans. A compression bandage may be applied for 10-15 minutes to aid reduction of oedema before attempting reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrethral catheterisation\u003C/strong\u003E should not be performed prior to reduction as it may increase tissue oedema and make reduction more difficult. Additionally, the presence of a catheter would physically interfere with the reduction manoeuvre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfiltration with adrenaline\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated and may cause tissue ischaemia. Ice packs or granulated sugar may be used topically to reduce oedema through osmotic effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical betamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is used for treating inflammatory conditions such as balanitis but has no role in acute paraphimosis management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECircumcision\u003C/strong\u003E or dorsal slit may be required if manual reduction fails, but this is rare if reduction is attempted early. These procedures should be considered only after failed conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral adjunctive measures can be used to facilitate manual reduction. Granulated sugar can be applied topically to promote osmotic fluid shifts and reduce oedema. Ice packs may also help reduce swelling. While surgical management with dorsal slit or circumcision is available if manual reduction fails, this is rarely necessary as most cases can be successfully reduced with conservative measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of paraphimosis can be treated by manual reduction after application of local anaesthetic and gentle compression.","Paraphimosis is a urological emergency requiring prompt treatment to prevent ischaemic complications.","Surgical management is rarely required if manual reduction is performed promptly."],"references":["Clifford ID, Craig SS, Nataraja RM, et al. Paediatric paraphimosis. Emerg Med Austral 2016; 28:96-99."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75436"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"421"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19046"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19046"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f9153a0-15ed-489f-aa3f-9c458530a787.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/3f9153a0-15ed-489f-aa3f-9c458530a787.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75436"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-